<p>A <b>hi-hat</b>, or <b>hihat</b>, is a type of <a href="Cymbal" title="Cymbal">cymbal</a> and stand used as a typical part of a <a href="Drum_kit" title="Drum kit">drum kit</a> by percussionists in <a href="Rhythm_and_blues" title="Rhythm and blues">R&amp;B</a>, <a href="Hip-hop_music" title="Hip-hop music" class="mw-redirect">hip-hop</a>, <a href="Disco" title="Disco">disco</a>, <a href="Jazz" title="Jazz">jazz</a>, <a href="Metal" title="Metal">metal</a>, <a href="Rock_and_roll" title="Rock and roll">rock and roll</a>, <a href="House_music" title="House music">house</a>, <a href="Reggae" title="Reggae">reggae</a> and other forms of contemporary popular music.<sup id="cite_ref-DRUMHISTORY_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DRUMHISTORY-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> It is a standard part of the modern drum kit. The hi-hat consists of two <a href="Cymbal" title="Cymbal">cymbals</a> that are mounted on a stand, one on top of the other, and a pedal which can be used to clash and hold the cymbals together.</p>
